==================================================
            SPRING FRAMEWORK NOTES
==================================================

1. WHAT IS SPRING?
--------------------------------------------------
Spring is a lightweight Java framework
used to develop enterprise applications.

Purpose:
- Simplifies Java development
- Provides loose coupling
- Manages object creation automatically


2. WHY SPRING?
--------------------------------------------------
Problems before Spring:
- Tight coupling
- Manual object creation
- Difficult maintenance and testing

Spring solves using:
- IOC-Inversion of Control
ðŸ‘‰ Control of object creation is given to the Spring container
ðŸ‘‰ Not handled by the developer manually

- DI-Dependency Injection 
ðŸ‘‰ Injecting dependent object into another object.

If Car needs Engine â†’ Engine is dependency.

Spring injects it automatically.

- AOP-Aspect Oriented Programming
ðŸ‘‰ Cross-cutting concerns

These are common functionalities used in many classes:

Logging

Security

Transactions

Exception handling


3. CORE CONCEPTS
--------------------------------------------------

3.1 Inversion of Control (IOC)
--------------------------------
- Spring controls object creation
- Developer does not use 'new' keyword
- Objects are managed by Spring container

Example:
Car object is created by Spring, not by programmer


3.2 Dependency Injection (DI)
--------------------------------
- Injecting dependent objects automatically

Types of DI:
1. Constructor Injection
2. Setter Injection
3. Field Injection


3.3 Bean
--------------------------------
- Bean is an object managed by Spring
- Bean lifecycle is controlled by Spring


3.4 Spring Container
--------------------------------
Responsible for:
- Creating beans
- Managing lifecycle
- Injecting dependencies

Types:
1. BeanFactory
2. ApplicationContext (most used)


4. SPRING MODULES
--------------------------------------------------

1. Spring Core
- IOC
- DI
- Bean management

2. Spring Context
- ApplicationContext
- Event handling
- Internationalization

3. Spring AOP
- Aspect Oriented Programming
- Cross-cutting concerns

4. Spring JDBC
- Simplifies JDBC code
- Removes boilerplate code

5. Spring ORM
- Hibernate / JPA integration

6. Spring MVC
- Web application framework
- MVC architecture


5. AOP (ASPECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING)
--------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
- Separate common logic from business logic

Cross-cutting concerns:
- Logging
- Security
- Transactions

AOP Terms:
- Aspect     : Extra functionality
- Advice     : When logic executes
- JoinPoint  : Where logic executes
- Pointcut   : Expression to match join points


6. SPRING CONFIGURATION TYPES
--------------------------------------------------

1. XML Configuration
- Uses XML files to define beans

2. Annotation Configuration
- Uses annotations like:
  @Component
  @Autowired
  @Service

3. Java Based Configuration
- Uses @Configuration and @Bean


7. IMPORTANT ANNOTATIONS
--------------------------------------------------

@Component    -> Marks class as Spring bean
@Service      -> Service layer
@Repository   -> DAO layer
@Controller   -> Controller layer
@Autowired    -> Inject dependency
@Configuration-> Configuration class
@Bean         -> Define bean method


8. SPRING BOOT (OVERVIEW)
--------------------------------------------------
Spring Boot is built on Spring framework

Features:
- Auto configuration
- Embedded server
- No XML configuration
- Faster development


9. ADVANTAGES OF SPRING
--------------------------------------------------
- Loose coupling
- Easy testing
- Modular framework
- Scalable applications
- Industry standard


10. INTERVIEW ONE-LINERS
--------------------------------------------------
IOC  -> Control of object creation by Spring
DI   -> Automatic dependency injection
Bean -> Object managed by Spring
AOP  -> Separation of cross-cutting concerns

